
[1]idiom

   ID'IOM, n. [L. idioma, from Gr. proper, or peculiar to one's self; Eng.
   widow, wide.]

   1. A mode of expression peculiar to a language; peculiarity of
   expression or phraseology. In this sense, it is used in the plural to
   denote forms of speech or phraseology, peculiar to a nation or
   language.

   And to just idioms fix our doubtful speech.

   2. The genius or peculiar east of a language.

   He followed the Latin language, but did not comply with the idiom of
   ours.

   3. Dialect.
